# Model the Video Resource in Local Convex

## Question

Domain-model the video resource in local Convex, mirroring course-builder's content-resource shape where it helps and dropping it where it doesn't. Must cover: lifecycle state (draft/published) crossed with visibility (public/unlisted/private); Mux identifiers (upload id, asset id, playback id(s), asset status); the source pointer and archive location; the share slug the watch URL is built from; who/what published it (Joel vs which agent — the agentic pipeline needs attribution); and timestamps enough to drive the originals TTL. Decide what is state-machine (can a published video go back to draft? what does deleting mean — Mux asset deleted, archive deleted, both?) and what indexes the watch page and CLI need. Grill via `/skill:grill-me` with `/skill:local-convex` loaded; blocked on the yoink audit because course-builder's videoResource/contentResource schemas are the reference input.

## Answer

Answered 2026-07-13 with Joel (grill in the steering session).

**Storage — video is just a type of content resource (Joel's call).** One row in the existing `contentResources` table (`apps/web/convex/schema.ts:125`) with `type: "videoResource"`; no Convex schema migration needed. The yoink audit's don't-copy-the-fields-bag warning is honored at the **code edge**, exactly as course-builder does it: a typed schema validates `fields` on every read and write (course-builder's reference: `packages/core/src/schemas/video-resource.ts` `VideoResourceSchema`; ours in Effect Schema to match the joelclaw-api stack). The raw bag is never passed around.

**Field set** — course-builder's base: `title`, `duration`, `resolution`, `muxAssetId`, `muxPlaybackId`, `transcript`, `srt`, `wordLevelSrt`, `chapters`, and the processing `state` enum (`new → processing → preparing → ready | errored`, plus `deleted`). JoelClaw deltas: `muxUploadId`, `staticRenditionStatus` (rendition readiness is a separate webhook state), **`lifecycle`** (`draft`/`published` — orthogonal to processing state), **`visibility`** (`public`/`unlisted`/`private`), **`shareSlug`** (short random unguessable, canonical) + **`vanityAlias`** (nullable — rides the shortlink system), **`publishedBy`** (attribution: joel or which agent), **`sourcePointer`** (`{host, path}`), **`archive`** (`{key, checksum, archivedAt}` — the TTL sweep contract), `publishedAt`.

**Identity & correlation:** `resourceId = "video:<shareSlug>"`. Mux `passthrough` carries the resourceId, so every webhook correlates through the existing `by_resourceId` index — **zero new indexes**. `searchText` gets title now, transcript when Deepgram lands.

**State machine:** processing state (Mux lifecycle) and publish lifecycle are independent axes. `draft ↔ published` flips freely (unpublish 404s the watch page). Delete = tombstone: `deletedAt` set in Convex (slug never re-minted, webhook stragglers land on a tombstone), Mux asset and Garage object hard-deleted.

**Write path:** through **joelclaw-api** — Joel's call (2026-07-13): a new generally-useful application layer (Hono?, pocock-quality TS 7, effect-smol v4, xstate v5, oxfmt/oxlint/ultracite; eventual MCP + CLI coverage) owns Convex mutations. Chartering it graduated to [Charter joelclaw-api](./charter-joelclaw-api.svx). Phase 1 keeps its stash-and-backfill fallback so the build never blocks on the new app.
